solutions.content:
I found the brilliant idea and clean code at [here](https://gist.github.com/wangming2046/b5ac650ac565c0e37fd5886b68339201), so I share it.
The key observations are same with problem's hint:
- Think of the L and R as people on a horizontal line, where X is a space.
- L can only go to left spaces, R can only go to right spaces and the people can't cross each other.

Assume the index of **first** `L` character in `start` string is `i`, we iterate `end` string to find index `j` of **first**  `L` character in `end`.
We can only convert `start` to `end` if  `i <= j`, otherwise it's impossible.
For example: the following case is okay
start = ".....L.."
end  = "..L....."

The same thinking when met `R` character in `start`, but because `R` can only go to right spaces, we can only convert `start` to `end` if `i >= j`.

Then, continue iterate `start` string and do same logic.

Algorithm:
- Define `j` pointer for `end` string.
- Iterate `start` string.
  - When met `L` in `start` string, increase `j` until `end.charAt(j) == 'L'`, if `j > i` return false
  - When met `R` in `start` string, increase `j` until `end.charAt(j) == 'R'`, if `j < i` return false

Implementation:

```java
class Solution {

  public boolean canTransform(String start, String end) {

    if (start.replace("X", "").length() != end.replace("X", "").length()) {
      return false;
    }

    int len = start.length();
    int j = 0;
    for (int i = 0; i < len; i++) {

      if (start.charAt(i) == 'L') {
        // find the next 'L' position in "end"
        while (j < len && end.charAt(j) != 'L') j += 1;

        // index of next 'L' in "end" > index of 'L' in "start", it's impossible to convert start to end.
        // For example:
        // start = "..L...."
        // end   = "....L.."
        if (j > i) return false;

        j += 1;
      }       

      if (start.charAt(i) == 'R') {
        // find the next 'R' position in "end"
        while (j < len && end.charAt(j) != 'R') j += 1;

        // index of next 'R' in "end" < index of 'R' in "start", it's impossible to convert start to end.
        // For example:
        // start = "....R..."
        // end   = "..R....."
        if (j < i) return false;

        j += 1;
      }      
    }

    return true;
  }
}
```

