solutions.content:
The basic idea is to count the number of R in start string, and the number of L in end string. 
The reason is that when we meet a 'R' in the end string, we hope there is a 'R' in the start string before. This is why we need to count the number of R in the start string.
And when we meet a 'L' in the start string, we hope we have meet a 'L' in the end string before.
If we didn't meet what we need before, return false, that is  (cnt_r < 0 || cnt_l < 0).
If we meet both 'L' and 'R', return false, because we cannot let a 'L' or 'R' go across each other, and that is (cnt_r > 0 && cnt_l > 0)

In the end, we hope all R and L have been used, that is return cnt_r == 0 && cnt_l == 0
```
    bool canTransform(string start, string end) {
        if(start.length() != end.length()) return false;
        int cnt_r = 0, cnt_l = 0;
        for(int i = 0, j = 0; i < start.size(), j < end.size(); i++, j++) {
            cnt_r += start[i] == 'R' ? 1 : 0;
            cnt_l += end[j] == 'L' ? 1 : 0;
            if(end[j] == 'R' && cnt_l == 0) cnt_r --;
            if(start[i] == 'L' && cnt_r == 0) cnt_l --;
            if(cnt_r < 0 || cnt_l < 0 || (cnt_r > 0 && cnt_l > 0)) return false;
        }
        return cnt_r == 0 && cnt_l == 0;
    }
