solutions.content:
Let j be the index that is the first that r[j] != r[i]. Moving i from 0 to n, if r[i] == s[i] then do nothing. When r[i] != s[i], it is only feasible to change r to match s if r[i] == 'R' or s[i] == 'L', and one of them is 'X'. In that case the right move is to move r[j] all the way back to i-th position in case r[i] = 'X' and r[j] ='L', or to move r[i] all the way to j-th position if r[i] ='R' and r[j] = 'X'. Either case is equivalent to swap(r[i], r[j]).
```
class Solution {
public:
    bool can(string r, string s) {
        int n = r.size();
        r += 'T';
        int i = 0, j = 0;
        while (i < n) {
            while (r[j] == r[i]) ++j;
            if (i >= 0 && s[i] != r[i]) {
                if (r[i] != 'X' && s[i] != 'X') return false;
                if (r[i] == 'R' || s[i] == 'L') {
                    if (r[j] != s[i]) return false;
                    swap(r[j],r[i]);
                }
                else return false;
            }
            ++i;
        }
        return true;
    }    

    bool canTransform(string r, string s) {
        if (r.size() != s.size()) return false;
        return can(r,s);
    }
};
```

