```
class Solution {
    public boolean canTransform(String start, String end) {
        char[] startChars = start.toCharArray();
        int n = startChars.length;
        int candidateNextL = -1;
        int candidateNextX = -1;
        for(int i=0; i<n; i++) {
            char target = end.charAt(i);
            if (startChars[i] == target) {
                // great, we match at this position
                continue;
            }
            if (target == 'R') {
                /*
                so we want an R. But we have X or L.
                We can't bring an R though either.
                R can only go Right
                */
                return false;
            } else if (target == 'L') {
                if (startChars[i] == 'R') {
                    // no L can make it's way left thru the R
                    return false;
                }
                /* ok so at an X. Keep scanning
                want something like X..XL
                that way can pull an L from right
                */
                int curr = Math.max(i+1, candidateNextL);
                while(curr < n && startChars[curr] == 'X') {
                    curr++;
                }
                if (curr == n) {
                    // reached end only found Xs no L to borrow
                    return false;
                }
                if (startChars[curr] == 'R') {
                    return false;
                }
                // great, finally found L after 1 or more X's so use it
                swap(curr, i, startChars);
                candidateNextL = curr + 1; // found all X's till curr and L is used..
            } else {
                // target = X
                if (startChars[i] == 'L') {
                    // L blocks.
                    return false;
                }
                // this time go thru all the filler R's
                int curr = Math.max(i+1, candidateNextX);
                while(curr < n && startChars[curr] == 'R') {
                    curr++;
                }
                if (curr == n) {
                    // reached end only found Rs no X to borrow
                    return false;
                }
                if (startChars[curr] == 'L') {
                    return false;
                }
                // great, finally found X after 1 or more R's so use it
                swap(curr, i, startChars);
                candidateNextX = curr + 1;
            }
        }
        return true;
    }

    private void swap(int pos1, int pos2, char[] arr) {
        char tmp = arr[pos1];
        arr[pos1] = arr[pos2];
        arr[pos2] = tmp;
    }
}

```

I looked at top recommended answers and didn't come up with the right and left "walkers" approach which in hindsight is really intuitive.  However, I went for an approach that seemed natural to me (didn't read Hint before solving): for every position ```i```, we try to make ```start[i] = end[i]``` and return ```false``` first time we are unable to.

There are 3 cases for mismatches ```start[i] != end[i]``` that we have to handle. 
1. Case ```end[i] == R```: return false on mismatch. X??? cannot transform to R??? as R can't migrate left and same for L???
2. Case ```end[i] == L```: If ```start[i] == R``` here then return false because R??? cannot transform into L??? because while L can migrate left thru X's it can't do so through an R. However if ```start[i] == X``` then X...XL (all intermediate are X's) can potentially transform into L??? because through a series of swaps we can borrow the first L after the Xs (ex. XXL -> XLX -> LXX).  Here is where the optimization happens: we store 1 past location of the L so in future don't have to double-scan past the X's.
3. Case ```end[i] == X```: Similar to prior case. If ```start[i] == L``` here then return false because L??? cannot transform into X??? because we can't pull an X through L. However if ```start[i] == R``` then R...RX (all intermediate are R's) can potentially transform into X??? because we can borrow the first X after the Rs (ex. RRX -> RXR -> XRR). Again same idea where we store 1 past location of discovered X to avoid double-scanning.

